<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920109-0059</DOCNO><DOCID>920109-0059.</DOCID><HL>   International Brief -- Ing. C. Olivetti andamp; C. S.p.A.:   Work Force to Be Reduced   By 3,000, Union Indicates</HL><DATE>01/09/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6</SO><CO>   I.OLV LABOR</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)</IN><NS>LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)</NS><RE>EUROPE (EU)GERMANY (GE)ITALY (ITA)SPAIN (SP)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   Italian office automation equipment maker Ing. C. Olivettiandamp; C. S.p.A. plans to cut about 2,500 jobs in Italy, orslightly more than 11% of its work force, union officialssaid. Another 500 jobs abroad, mostly in Germany and Spain,will be trimmed, they added.   Although the specifics of the plan couldn't immediately beconfirmed by officials at Olivetti's headquarters in Ivrea,Carlo De Benedetti, the company's chairman and chiefexecutive officer, late last year said further job cuts wouldbe necessary.</LP><TEXT>   Yesterday, Olivetti management started a round of talkswith labor unions on its &quot;industrial plan&quot; for the currentyear.   Olivetti has planned the payroll cuts to reduce operatingcosts and overcome the current crisis in the internationalcomputer industry. Following several years of decliningearnings, Olivetti is expected to post a loss for 1991 forthe first time in 13 years.   Mr. De Benedetti, who also is the group's controllingshareholder, in November took over direct management controland launched a major restructuring aimed at cutting operatingcosts.</TEXT></DOC>